If one angle of the parallelogram is 120 degrees, then another angle between adjacent sides has measure $180^\circ - 120^\circ = 60^\circ$.  Shown in the diagram above, let the parallelogram be $ABCD$, with $\overline{AD}$ one of the short sides.  Drawing the altitude from $D$ to $\overline{AB}$ gives us 30-60-90 triangle $AXD$, from which we find $XD = (AD/2)\sqrt{3} = 4\sqrt{3}$, so the area of $ABCD$ is $(AB)(XD) = \boxed{60\sqrt{3}}$. The answer is 60\sqrt{3}.

