Let $A$, $B$, and $C$ be the vertices of the triangle so that angle $A$ measures 45 degrees and angle $C$ measures 30 degrees.  Define $D$ to be the foot of the perpendicular from $B$ to side $AC$.  Because angle $A$ measures 45 degrees and angle $ADB$ is a right angle, triangle $ADB$ is a 45-45-90 triangle.  Since the length of a leg of a 45-45-90 triangle is $\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$ times the length of the hypotenuse, $AD=BD=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cdot 6\sqrt{2}=6$ units.  Also, $CDB$ is a 30-60-90 triangle, so we can multiply the short leg $BD$ by 2 to find the length of the hypotenuse and by $\sqrt{3}$ to find the length of the longer leg.  This gives $BC=12$ units and $CD=6\sqrt{3}$ units.  The sum of the lengths of sides $AC$ and $BC$ is $6+6\sqrt{3}+12=18+6\sqrt{3}$.  To the nearest tenth of a unit, this is $\boxed{28.4}$ units. [asy]
